Philipp Walter

Hi,

I come to a similar solution using print(f"{item.name}\t\t${item.price:>6.2f}\t\t{item.quantity}\t${total_price:>6.2f}") and asked myself if there is a possibility not to repeat myself specifying the :>6.2f.

Here is the according version (supported by copilot ;-) and yes I just focused on the pricing formatting and think that "\t" isnt the best solution of formatting whole table.

def print_items(items: list[Item], total:Decimal, price_format: str):
print("Shopping Cart:")
print(f"Item\t\t{'Price':>7}\t\tQty\tTotal")
print("=" * LEN_LINES)
for item in items:
total_price = item.price * item.quantity
print(f"{item.name}\t\t{price_format.format(item.price)}\t\t{item.quantity}\t{price_format.format(total_price)}")
print("=" * LEN_LINES)
print(f"Total:\t{price_format.format(total)}")

def main():
# Create a shopping cart
items = [
Item("Apple", Decimal("1.50"), 10),
Item("Banana", Decimal("2.00"), 2),
Item("Pizza", Decimal("11.90"), 5),
]

total = Decimal(sum(item.price * item.quantity for item in items))

print_items(items, total, "${:6.2f}" )
print_items(items, total, "€{:6.2f}" )

Hi, I have implemented two solutions:

The fisrt one:
from dataclasses import dataclass
from decimal import Decimal

@dataclass
class Item:
name: str
price: Decimal
quantity: int

def main():
# Create a shopping cart
items = [
Item("Apple", Decimal("1.50"), 10),
Item("Banana", Decimal("2.00"), 2),
Item("Pizza", Decimal("11.90"), 5),
]

total = sum(item.price * item.quantity for item in items)

# Print the cart
print("Shopping Cart:")

item_title = "Item"
price_title = "Price"
qty_title = "Qty"
total_title = "Total"
symbol = "$"

print(f"{item_title} {price_title:>13} {qty_title:>9} {total_title:>11}")

for item in items:
total_price = item.price * item.quantity
print(f"{item.name:<11}{symbol:<1}{item.price:6}{item.quantity:10}{symbol:>6}{total_price:6}")
print("=" * 40)
print(f"Total:{symbol:>2}{total:6}")

if __name__ == "__main__":
main()
*********************

The second one:

from dataclasses import dataclass, field
from decimal import Decimal

@dataclass
class Item:
name: str
price: Decimal
quantity: int
symbol: str = "$"
total_price: Decimal = field(init=False)

def __post_init__(self) -> None:
self.total_price = self.quantity * self.price

def __str__(self) -> str:
return f"{self.name:<11}{self.symbol:<1}{self.price:6}{self.quantity:10}{self.symbol:>6}{self.total_price:6}"

def main():
# Create a shopping cart
items = [
Item("Apple", Decimal("1.50"), 10),
Item("Banana", Decimal("2.00"), 2),
Item("Pizza", Decimal("11.90"), 5),
]

total = sum(item.total_price for item in items)

# Print the cart
print("Shopping Cart:")

item_title = "Item"
price_title = "Price"
qty_title = "Qty"
total_title = "Total"
simbol = "$"

print(f"{item_title} {price_title:>13} {qty_title:>9} {total_title:>11}")

for item in items:
print(item)
print("=" * 40)
print(f"Total:{simbol:>2}{total:6}")

if __name__ == "__main__":
main()

Raegan Barker

Fun little challenge!

Two small things I did differently:
1. Defined the formatted column headers as a separate string before printing it. That way I could use len(header) to dynamically drive the number of times to repeat the "=" character line.
2. Used f"{item.name:<10.10}" where the .10 acts as a truncation length if Item.name is too long.
